.<img width="1280" height="720" class="wp-image-1656791" style="width: 800px;" src="https://cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/VAT-banner-1280x720-1.jpg" alt="VAT" srcset="https://cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/VAT-banner-1280x720-1.jpg?width=1280&amp;auto_optimize=medium 1280w, https://cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/VAT-banner-1280x720-1-300x169.jpg?width=300&amp;auto_optimize=medium 300w, https://cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/VAT-banner-1280x720-1-1024x576.jpg?width=1024&amp;auto_optimize=medium 1024w, https://cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/VAT-banner-1280x720-1-768x432.jpg?width=768&amp;auto_optimize=medium 768w, https://cdn.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/VAT-banner-1280x720-1-1200x675.jpg?width=1200&amp;auto_optimize=medium 1200w" sizes="(max-width: 1280px) 100vw, 1280px" /> By Innocent Anaba, LAGOS THE Attorneys-General of the 36 states of the Federation will be meeting in Lagos from today, to discuss some critical legal issues bordering on Value Added Tax, Paris Club Refunds and Stamp Duty, among others. The meeting, which is scheduled for June 15 through 17, 2022, will see the Chairman of the Nigerian Southern Governors’ Forum and Ondo State Governor, Rotimi Akeredolu, deliver the keynote address at the opening session. Other issues to be discussed by the state Attorneys-General include the proposed amendments to the Stamp Duties Act, pensions and gratuity for judges, and amendments to the 1999 Constitution, Anti-Corruption Commission established by states, and Federal Inland Revenue Service, IRS, threat to recovering ‘unremitted tax deductions by states’ and local governments. Governors of Babajide Sanwo-Olu and Simon Lalong of Lagos and Plateau states respectively are expected to address the meeting. Others billed to speak at the meeting include Attorneys-General of the Federation and Minister of Justice, Abubakar Malami, SAN; Nigeria Bar Association, NBA, President, Mr Olumide Akpata, and the Director-General of the Nigerian Governor’s Forum, Asishana Okauru.